               <msContents>
                  <summary>A complete copy of the <title>Khizānah-ʼi ʻĀmirah</title> (Royal
                     Treasury), originally composed by <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc"
                        type="standard" role="aut" key="person_90779326"
                        ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/90779326/">Ghulām ʻAlī ibn Nūḥ Āzād Bilgrāmī
                        (1704–1786)</persName> in <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari" when="1762">1176 AH
                        (1762–63 CE)</date> in <placeName type="city"
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/1140111" key="place_1140111"
                        >Aurangabad</placeName>, then capital of the <placeName type="state"
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/8698275" key="place_8698275">Princely
                        State of Hyderabad</placeName>, shortly after his friend and patron
                        <persName role="subject" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/13156856205549600715"
                        key="person_13156856205549600715"><addName type="honourific"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/13156856205549600715"
                           key="person_13156856205549600715">Niẓām al-Mulk</addName> ‘Alī Khān
                           <addName type="epithet" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/13156856205549600715"
                           key="person_13156856205549600715">Āṣaf Jāh II</addName> (b. 1734, r.
                        1762–1803)</persName> ascended the throne. A major poet and author of
                     several historical and biographical accounts, in this work he relates the lives
                     of some 135 Persian poets with selections of their oeuvre, recounts the history
                     of the Āsaf Jahi dynasty up to his patron, and also covers the reigns of
                        <persName ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/139145910119027021680"
                        key="person_139145910119027021680" role="subject">Aḥmad Shāh Durranī (b.
                        1722, r. 1747–1772)</persName> and the <placeName
                        ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/138609323" role="subject">Maratha
                        empire</placeName>. Since he lived during many of these events and relates
                     vivid eyewitness accounts, historians deem it a reliable source on <date
                        calendar="#Gregorian" notBefore="1699" notAfter="1801">18th-century</date>
                     South Asia. </summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_319-item1">
                     <author key="person_90779326" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/90779326/">
                        <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="standard">Āzād Bilgrāmī, Ghulām ʻAlī
                           ibn Nūḥ, 1704–1786</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa">آزاد، سيد غلام علي,</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_890">Khizānah-'i ʻĀmirah</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa" key="work_890">خزانۀ عامره</title>
                     <incipit xml:lang="fa"><locus from="1b" to="1b"> برگ ۱پ (folio 1b):</locus> سر
                        کلام راجعه حمد صانعیست که انسان را به گوهر گرانمایه ناطقه بنواخت.</incipit>
                     <explicit xml:lang="ar"><locus from="267a" to="267a"> برگ ۲۶۷ر (folio
                           267a):</locus> سبحان ربك رب العزة عما يصفون وسلام على المرسلين والحمد لله
                        رب العالمين. </explicit>
                     <colophon>No colophon.</colophon>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                     <note>
                        <persName type="standard" role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/49606162"
                           key="person_49606162">Sir Alexander Malet (1800–1886)</persName>
                        presented this volume to the Oriental Translation Committee of the <orgName
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/132108036" role="fmo">Royal Asiatic Society of
                           Great Britain and Ireland</orgName>. It seems that scholar <persName
                           type="standard" role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/20108923/"
                           key="person_20108923">Nathaniel Bland (1803-1865)</persName> borrowed the
                        volume to prepare his groundbreaking essay on biographies of Persian poets
                        published in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1848">1848</date>, but then
                        never returned it before his death. The text appears complete, albeit with
                        variations when compared to the lithographed edition published by <orgName
                           role="pbl edt" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/263714350"
                           key="person_263714350">Naval Kishore Press</orgName> in <date
                           calendar="#Hijri-qamari" when="1871">1287 AH (1871 CE)</date>. For a
                        complete description of the contents, see Sachau and Ethé's Bodleian Library
                        catalogue, no. 381. For another complete copy, see Rylands <ref
                           target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_7437"><idno>Persian
                              MS 925</idno></ref> and for and for an adridged redaction, see <ref
                           target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6813"><idno>Persian
                              MS 320</idno></ref>.</note>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="chart">
                        <support><p>Textblock comprised of sized and polished, cross-grained,
                              cream-coloured <material>paper</material> handmade in <country
                                 cert="high" ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208"
                                 >India</country>.</p></support>
                        <extent><measure unit="folio" quantity="267">267 folios 2 flyleaves (ff. i +
                              267 + i )</measure>. <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                              <height>210</height>
                              <width>120</width>
                           </dimensions>
                           <dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
                              <height>160</height>
                              <width>82</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>
                        <foliation>Incomplete modern foliation in pencilled Arabic numberals
                           subsequently completed by the cataloguer. Note that foliation commences
                           on the second folio of the text proper.</foliation>
                        <collation>Undetermined. <catchwords>Catchwords on b side of nearly every
                              folio.</catchwords></collation>
                        <condition>
                           <p>In poor condition with insect damage mainly at the tail, and fore-edge
                              embrittled, and a large tear on <locus from="253" to="253">folio
                                 253</locus>.</p>
                        </condition>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="1" writtenLines="21">
                           <p>Written in 1 column, with 21 lines per page. Ruled with a <hi
                                 rend="italic">misṭarah</hi> hand guide.</p>
                        </layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote scope="major" script="nasta_liq" medium="ink">
                        <desc>Text copied in a small nasta'liq hand in <material>black</material>
                           with occasional shikastah ligatures and finials, with subheaders in
                              <material>red</material>.</desc>
                     </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <additions><lb/>
                     <label>Inscriptions:</label>
                     <list rend="bulleted">
                        <item> Inscribed on <locus from="iia" to="iia">the first folio obverse (f.
                              iia)</locus> by former owner <persName type="standard" role="fmo ins"
                              ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/49606162" key="person_49606162">Sir
                              Alexander Malet (1800–1886), second baronet</persName>, when he
                           presented it to the Oriental Translation Committee of the <orgName
                              role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/132108036">Royal Asiatic Society
                              of Great Britain and Ireland</orgName>: <q xml:lang="en">Presented to
                              the Com. Oriental Translation by Sir A-Malet Bart</q>. </item>
                        <item>The <locus from="right_paste-down" to="right_paste-down">right paste
                              down</locus> inscribed with the number <q xml:lang="en">20</q>.</item>
                        <item>The <locus from="ia" to="ia"> first right flyleaf obverse (f.
                              ia)</locus> inscribed with the title of the work in both Persian and
                           transliterated Latin characters.</item>
                        <item>Folios <locus from="72b" to="72b">72b</locus>, <locus from="134a"
                              to="134a">folio 134a</locus>, and <locus from="234b" to="234b">folio
                              235b</locus> bear marginalia in nasta‘līq script in
                              <material>black</material>.</item>
                     </list>
                     <label>Bookplates:</label> The <locus from="Inner_back_cover"
                        to="Inner_back_cover">left pastedown</locus>: <q xml:lang="en">'Bibliotheca
                        Lindesiana</q> with shelfmark <q xml:lang="en">21/k</q> and <q xml:lang="en"
                           ><hi rend="strikethrough">Bland</hi> MSS No. <hi rend="strikethrough"
                           >526</hi></q>, with the name and number crossed out and <q xml:lang="en"
                        >Persian</q> and <q xml:lang="en">319</q> written aside.</additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding calendar="#Gregorian" notBefore="1750" notAfter="1800">
                        <p>Sewn on three supports, probably on sawn-in <material>cords</material>.
                           Originally bound in dark reddish-brown, highly polished full goatskin
                              <material>leather</material> over <material>pasteboards</material>
                           without a flap (type III binding as per Déroche). Later repairs to the
                              <locus from="Spine" to="Spine">spine</locus> and fore-edge in
                           sheepskin <material>leather</material>. Yellow wove endpapers, the left
                           one watermarked <watermark><q xml:lang="en">J Whatman <date
                                    calendar="#Gregorian" when="1827">1827</date></q></watermark>,
                           of the <orgName type="display" role="ppm"
                              ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/307449418" key="person_307449418">Whatman
                              Paper Mill</orgName> in <placeName><settlement type="town"
                                 ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/151287843">Maidstone</settlement>,
                                 <settlement type="county" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/148861381"
                                 >Kent</settlement></placeName>, then owned and operated by
                              <persName type="display" role="ppm"
                              ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/54948875" key="person_54948875">William
                              Balston (1759–1849)</persName>, probably added to the volume when
                           restored.</p>
                        <decoNote type="binding"><p>stamped paper onlays with floral designs in the
                              central mandorla, detached pendants, irises in the corners, framed by
                              a flower garland on the border.</p></decoNote>
                        <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                              <height>210</height>
                              <width>131</width>
                              <depth>33</depth>
                           </dimensions></p>
                        <condition>Handle with caution. In fair condition. Original boards abraded,
                           with the corners bumped and exposed. Later sheepskin
                              <material>leather</material>repairs now degraded. Paper <locus
                              from="Spine" to="Spine">spine</locus> label severely darkened and
                           degraded.</condition>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin> Probably Northern <origPlace cert="high"
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208">India></origPlace>
                     <origDate cert="medium" calendar="#Gregorian" notBefore="1750" notAfter="1800">
                        undated, but probably completed in the late eighteenth century.</origDate>
                  </origin>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>Probably acquired in the <placeName cert="high"
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208" key="place_7000208">Indian
                           subcontinent</placeName> by British diplomat <persName type="standard"
                           role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/49606162" key="person_49606162">Sir
                           Alexander Malet (1800–1886), second baronet</persName>, who presented it
                        to the Oriental Translation Committee of the <orgName
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/132108036">Royal Asiatic Society of Great
                           Britain and Ireland</orgName> (see note on <locus from="iia" to="iia"
                           >folio iia</locus>).</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Evidently borrowed from the library by Persian scholar <persName
                           type="standard" role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/20108923/"
                           key="person_20108923">Nathaniel Bland (1803-1865)</persName>, likely in
                        preparation for his essay, but then never returned before his death.
                           <placeName ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/261467287">London</placeName>
                        antiquarian bookseller <persName type="standard" role="bsl"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/5679225/" key="person_5679225">Bernard Quaritch
                           (1819–1899)</persName> assumed it belonged to Bland (he added the Bland
                        bookplates), when he sold the volume with the rest of that collection to
                           <persName type="standard" role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/"
                           key="person_97751058">Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford
                           (1812–1880)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1866"
                           >1866</date>.</p>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>Purchased by <persName type="standard" role="dnr" key="person_f6379"
                           >Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                           when="1901">1901</date> from <persName type="standard" role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/" key="person_9985420">James Ludovic
                           Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847–1913)</persName>.</p>
                  </provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Bequeathed by <persName type="standard" role="dnr" key="person_f6379"
                           >Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                           when="1908">1908</date> to the <orgName type="corporation" role="rps"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John Rylands Library</orgName>.</p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>
